{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This is a family of prokaryotic phosphatases that hydrolyse non-canonical purine nucleotides such as XTP and ITP to their respective diphosphate derivatives. They probably exclude non-canonical purines from DNA precursor pool, thus preventing their incorporation into DNA and avoiding chromosomal lesions. ITP is the best substrate, followed by XTP, GDP or dITP [[cite:PUB00037841]].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Proteins in this entry include YjjX from E. coli. YjjX hydrolyzes non-canonical purine nucleotides such as XTP and ITP to their respective diphosphate derivatives. However, it is not active on dATP and dGTP, and exhibits no phosphatase activity toward pyrimidines (CTP, TTP, UTP, dCTP, and dTTP) [[cite:PUB00037841]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "1u14", "name" "The crystal structure of hypothetical UPF0244 protein yjjX at resolution 1.68 Angstrom"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR029001", "name" "Inosine triphosphate pyrophosphatase-like", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"hamap" {"MF_00648" "Inosine/xanthosine triphosphatase"}, "ncbifam" {"TIGR00258" "inosine/xanthosine triphosphatase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Inosine/xanthosine triphosphatase", "short" "Non_canon_purine_NTPase"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 4, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 824, "taxa" 4818, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 4295, "sets" 0, "proteins" 4294, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 3349}, "pathways" 2}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of enzymes. It is primarily based on the recommendations of the Nomenclature Committee of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (IUBMB) and it describes each type of characterized enzyme for whic